								<div class="title" id="post-title-4079550">
																		I&#039;m reviewing art pages - SpookyPizza
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wydness" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4862958); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=4862958&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205756" alt="Wydness" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=4862958)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wydness" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4862958); return false;" >Wydness</a></span> <span class="odate time_1544248690 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Dec 2018 05:58</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4079550">
									

<p>I think there's a lot that could be improved here, starting with the line work. When you use the line tool, the end result looks very rough, stiff, and unnatural. But when you freehand the lines, the result looks very plain and unconfident. This could be a problem of the art program or tools you have available. I also think you should work on shading and lighting more. It looks very fuzzy, and you seem to be at a point where you understand what shading <em>is</em> but don't quite know how to apply it yet. Practicing this would probably make the colors look more natural too. But the comparatively low quality of many of these drawings is strange to me when your more atmospheric pieces look really nice. 2237, 2400, 2719, and 2070 are much better executed and could definitely look great as wallpapers or posters. I think you could be great at drawing environments and backgrounds if you focused your attention there.</p>
<p>-1</p>

							</div>

								
